🌳 The Ideal Monorepo Structure for GitHub
Your current structure is already a perfect Monorepo foundation. When you add Django and React, it will naturally evolve into this enterprise layout:


document-studio/               <-- 📦 THIS IS YOUR SINGLE GITHUB REPO
│
├── services/                  <-- 🚀 Deployable Microservices
│   ├── studio-core/           <-- Rust Engine (Your current code)
│   ├── studio-api/            <-- Django Backend (Future)
│   └── studio-web/            <-- React/TipTap Frontend (Future)
│
├── infrastructure/            <-- 🏗️ DevOps & Deployment
│   ├── docker/                <-- Dockerfiles
│   ├── k8s/                   <-- Kubernetes manifests
│   └── terraform/             <-- Cloud provisioning
│
├── tests/                     <-- 🧪 Global Testing
│   ├── e2e/                   <-- Python E2E tests (spins up all services)
│   └── fixtures/              <-- Shared JSON payloads
│
├── docs/                      <-- 📖 Documentation & Examples
│   ├── architecture.md
│   └── examples/              <-- Generated PDFs/HTMLs
│
├── assets/                    <-- 🖼️ Shared static assets (logos, fonts)
├── docker-compose.yml         <-- 🐳 One command to run the whole stack locally
├── Makefile                   <-- 🛠️ Global build/test commands
└── README.md

Tip: You don't need to reorganize your folders today. Just keep your current DocumentStudio root as the GitHub repo, and when you create the Django/React apps, just put them in a services/ or apps/ folder at the root level.


